    description: "Given a BST and two nodes p and q, find their lowest common ancestor (LCA). LCA is the deepest node that is an ancestor of both p and q.",
    example: { input: "root=[6,2,8,0,4,7,9], p=2, q=8", output: "6" },
    hints: ["In a BST: if both p,q < node → go left. If both > node → go right. Else: current node is LCA.", "No need to traverse entire tree.", "Iterative version is cleaner than recursive."],
    clarify: { question: "What would you clarify?", options: ["Are p and q guaranteed to exist in the tree?","Can p or q be the root?","What if p==q?","Is it a BST or general binary tree?","Can LCA be p or q itself?"], mustAsk: [0,3,4], explanation: "p and q are guaranteed to exist. p or q can be root. p==q: LCA is that node. BST (not general) — exploit BST property. LCA can be p or q itself (if one is ancestor of other)." },
    steps: [
      { id: "understand", label: "Problem Understanding", emoji: "🔍", prompt: "What makes BST LCA different from general binary tree LCA? How does the BST property help?", why: { question: "Why can you find BST LCA without searching both subtrees?", options: ["BST doesn't help","BST property tells you which subtree contains each node. No need to search blindly — navigate directly to LCA.","Must still search both"], correct: 1, explanation: "In BST: if p and q are both < current, go left. If both >, go right. First node where they split (or equal current) = LCA. O(h) not O(n)." } },
      { id: "brute", label: "Brute Force", emoji: "🔨", prompt: "How would you find LCA in a general binary tree (ignoring BST property)?", why: { question: "Why is general binary tree LCA O(n)?", options: ["It's always O(h)","Must search entire tree: for each node, recursively check if p and q are in subtrees. No shortcut without BST property.","O(log n) with any binary tree"], correct: 1, explanation: "General binary tree: must check both subtrees at every node. O(n) total. BST LCA: O(h) by leveraging ordering property — far more efficient." } },
      { id: "pattern", label: "Pattern Recognition", emoji: "🧩", prompt: "State the three cases: both left, both right, split/equal. What does 'split' mean?", why: { question: "What does it mean when p.val < node.val < q.val (assuming p<q)?", options: ["Go right","Current node is LCA — p is in left subtree, q is in right subtree. They diverge here.","Go left"], correct: 1, explanation: "Split: one target is in each subtree. Current node = LCA. Also LCA if node.val == p.val or node.val == q.val (node IS one of the targets)." } },
      { id: "algorithm", label: "Algorithm Design", emoji: "⚙️", prompt: "Walk through the iterative algorithm (often preferred over recursive for this problem).", why: { question: "Why is iterative LCA preferred over recursive for BST?", options: ["Recursive is always preferred","Iterative: O(1) space. Recursive: O(h) call stack. Since we only go one direction at a time, iterative is natural and space-efficient.","Same complexity"], correct: 1, explanation: "BST LCA only ever goes in one direction — no need for recursion. Iterative while loop is O(h) time, O(1) space. Simpler than managing recursive call frames." } },
      { id: "tradeoff", label: "Trade-off", emoji: "⚖️", prompt: "BST LCA O(h) vs general binary tree LCA O(n). What if the BST is unbalanced?", why: { question: "What's the time complexity of BST LCA for a completely unbalanced (skewed) tree?", options: ["O(log n)","O(n) — skewed tree has h=n. BST property still helps compared to general binary tree, but worst case is still O(n).","O(h) is always O(log n)"], correct: 1, explanation: "h = O(log n) balanced, O(n) skewed. So BST LCA = O(h) which is O(log n) best case, O(n) worst case. Balanced BST (AVL/RB): always O(log n)." } },
      { id: "complexity", label: "Complexity", emoji: "📊", prompt: "Time and space for iterative vs recursive?", why: { question: "Space advantage of iterative approach?", options: ["No advantage","Iterative: O(1) space. Recursive: O(h) call stack (O(log n) balanced, O(n) skewed).","Recursive uses O(1) space"], correct: 1, explanation: "Iterative: single pointer, O(1) extra space. Recursive: implicit call stack = height of path traversed = O(h)." } },
      { id: "edge", label: "Edge Cases", emoji: "🔐", prompt: "What edge cases exist?", why: { question: "p is an ancestor of q — what is the LCA?", options: ["The node above p","p itself — p is the deepest node that is ancestor of both p and q.","q"], correct: 1, explanation: "If p is ancestor of q, LCA = p. When traversal reaches p, p.val equals one target → LCA = p. Algorithm handles this via the 'node equals target' case." } },
    ],
    dryrun: { question: "BST root=6, p=2, q=4. Step 1: both 2 and 4 < 6 → go left to node 2. Step 2: p=2 equals node 2 → LCA is node 2. What is returned?", options: ["6","2","4"], correct: 1, explanation: "At root=6: both p=2 and q=4 < 6 → go left. At node=2: p.val=2 == node.val=2 → current node is LCA. Return node 2. (This also means p is ancestor of q.)" },
    pushback: { challenge: "What if it's a general binary tree (not BST)?", options: ["DFS returning which targets are in each subtree. If both found in different subtrees or node equals target and the other is found below — that's LCA. O(n).","Use BST algorithm anyway","Doesn't work without BST property"], correct: 0, explanation: "General tree LCA: recurse(node) returns node if it equals p or q, returns null if subtree contains neither, returns the node if subtree has both. First node that gets both from children = LCA. O(n)." },
    followup: { question: "What if you need LCA of multiple nodes (not just two)?", options: ["Find LCA of all pairs incrementally: LCA(LCA(n1,n2), n3)... or track all target nodes in a set and check during traversal. O(n×k) for k targets.","Not possible","Same algorithm for two nodes"], correct: 0, explanation: "LCA of k nodes: general tree DFS counts how many targets are in each subtree. First node where count == k = LCA of all. O(n) regardless of k." },
    solution: { approach: "Iterative BST Navigation", steps: ["node = root","While node: if both p,q < node: node=node.left","Elif both p,q > node: node=node.right","Else: return node (split or match)"], time: "O(h)", space: "O(1)" },
